      "content": "To address your concerns about tracking down memory leaks in real-time without impacting CPU performance, you can consider the following strategies:\n\n1. **Custom Deleter**: Implement a custom deleter for your `std::vector` or any other container you're using. This deleter can log a message whenever an element is removed, which can help you trace back to the source of the leak.\n\n2. **Reference Counting**: If you're using smart pointers, you can implement a lightweight reference counting system that increments and decrements counts as objects are created and destroyed. When the count drops to zero, you can log a message indicating that an object is being deleted.\n\n3. **Memory Pool**: Create a memory pool for your `DataLog` objects. This pool can keep track of allocated blocks and their sizes. When a block is returned to the pool, you can log its size and the time it was returned. This can help you identify objects that are not being properly freed.\n\n4. **Periodic Audits**: Implement a periodic audit function that scans through your objects and checks for any that haven't been deleted yet. This function can run at a low frequency (e.g., every few minutes) to minimize performance impact.\n\n5. **Instrumentation",
